creator: Justin Masterson
title: IMG_4362.JPG
meta_data: {"pub_date": "1206741968", "date_taken": "2008-03-27 11:11:13", "description": "A statue of Jesus inside a hand-built grotto.\\n\\n--\\n(Adapted from the description at RoadsideAmerica.com)\\n\\nIn 1932, in the heart of the Great Depression, Centerville native Ben Hartman began what would become a decade-long project:  an impossibly large and complex sculpture garden made entirely of small stones, in his backyard.\\n\\nHartman's Rock Garden began small, as do many instances of Dementia Concretia -- Ben just wanted to build a little stone and concrete fish pond in his yard. He liked the finished product, and decided that he wasn't finished after all. He scavenged stone from a nearby construction site, broke it with his hammer, added bits of mirror and pottery -- and began building little stone houses, cathedrals, and parapets with religious statuary in the side and back yards of his wood-frame home. He kept building for seven years. He had the corner lot, so his work was easy to see.\\n\\nBen built a replica of Philadelphia's Independence Hall, a White House, a Mount Vernon (Ohioans can't get enough of mini-Mt. Vernons -- we saw another in Lima). A large castle with a drawbridge and moat is composed of 14,000 stones; a "Tree of Life" has over 20,000.\\n\\nBen stopped building in 1939. We suspect that he ran out of space, materials, maybe energy -- but certainly not ideas. He used something like a quarter of a million stones to create Hartman's Rock Garden.\\n\\nAlthough Ben died in 1944, his property was maintained by his wife Mary for many years, and even won the Community Beautification Award four times in the 60's.  The garden is now owned by Hartman's son, Ben Jr., and did not appear to be any longer upkept or maintained...pieces were falling apart, and weeds grew throughout (though this may just be a season growth).\\n\\nBetween the buildings (aside from the overgrowth) are little scenes -- a mix of history, religion, and Depression-era pop culture. Lawn statues of the Holy Family share space with garden gnomes. Small hand-written signs help visitors to distinguish one tableau from the next: Custer's Last Stand, Daniel in the Lion's Den, Noah's Ark, and "Foot path to Pece" (Peace).\\n\\n"The sad part of war" is rendered with little army men, fallen or missing limbs, and accompanied by angels. Meanwhile, a healthier army prepares to storm the castle...\\n\\nBen built a depiction of the Oregon Trail, a Nativity scene, a cup and saucer. Scenes of boxer Joe Louis and the Dionne Quintuplets -- a media sensation of Canadian multiple births -- suggest what occupied the popular imagination in the 1930s.\\n\\nOur favorite hand-lettered sign: \\n\\n"Behold thy mother and don't forget your Dad.""}

creator: Randy Wick
title: day 58 - Objects in Time
meta_data: {"pub_date": "1217304460", "date_taken": "2008-07-27 15:28:09", "description": "Watching these tiny bits of water travel made me think of the ephemeral nature of life itself.  \\n\\nWe existed, as did this trickling waterfall, in this moment, alone, together, and only for the moment.  Creeks combine with creeks to form streams, to form rivers, and to form lakes, seas, and oceans.  Permanent, yet fleeting.  Something, yet nothing.  Grandiose plans twist in the currents, and become mere whispers in the forest.  And soon I'll be gone: fate, destiny... gravity.\\n\\nWhat do you call it when reason is enthusiastically cast aside, and pain welcomed over comfort?"}

creator: UGArdener
title: Charleston Farmhouse Garden, Sussex
meta_data: {"pub_date": "1217378507", "date_taken": "2008-07-11 10:03:00", "description": "Charleston Farmhouse and Garden, located on the South Downs outside the village of Firle, near Alfriston, East Sussex, was the home or weekend and holiday retreat of Bloomsbury Group figures Vanessa Bell and Clive Bell, Vanessa\\u2019s companion Duncan Grant, and Vanessa\\u2019s children, Quentin and Julian, from 1916 until the 1960\\u2019s. On a Friday afternoon in July, we toured Charleston with Flickr contact Penwren, who graciously met us in Alfriston and first showed us the village and church in Firle, where Duncan Grant, Vanessa Bell and Quentin Bell are buried.\\nPhotography is not allowed in the house itself, so these pictures are of the garden only. The house itself was indescribable, with every square inch covered in enchanting Modernist artwork of all kinds, and the guided tour, lasting over an hour, was outstandingly well presented and informative.\\nPenwren added the following comment to one of the pictures in this set: Sir Peter Shepheard, in charge of the restoration (of the garden in the 1980\\u2019s), has described it as an "apotheosis of the traditional English cottage garden." He wrote notes to remind himself to "avoid neatness". Like the house, it was not intended to be tasteful or restrained. Interestingly, the garden has been organic since the 80s.\\nThe story of Charleston and its occupants is told very well in the book Charleston, a Bloomsbury House and Garden, by Quentin Bell and his daughter, Virginia Nicholson (Frances Lincoln \\u2013 paperback edition 2004). Alibris.com had numerous copies available in August, 2008 at: www.alibris.com/booksearch?qwork=1025402 &matches=16&a...\\nWe also enjoyed two small books published by Snake River Press and available by mail or in person at the excellent Much Ado Books in Alfriston: Bloomsbury in Sussex, and 20 Sussex Gardens (https://muchadobooks.com)\\n\\nThe list of visitors reads like a Who's Who of English intellectual and artistic life in the first half of the 20th Century: Leonard and Virginia Woolf (Vanessa's sister), Lytton Strachey, John Maynard Keynes, T.S. Elliot, Benjamin Britten are just a few."}

creator: Alan Stanton
title: The Borough of Waltham Forest complies with the law
meta_data: {"pub_date": "1218293540", "date_taken": "2008-08-07 23:17:08", "description": "7 August 2008. Two utterly tedious photos for anyone who has never had a parking ticket.\\n\\nAnd probably for most people who have. But stick with it, and I'll let you into three nasty little secrets.\\n\\n\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\xaf\\nWhat's going on here? \\n\\nThese are road markings in a Controlled Parking Zone (CPZ) in the London Borough of Waltham Forest. Nothing special about them; just where Zena and I were visiting friends in August 2008.\\n\\nNor is there anything out of the ordinary about the double yellow lines. In the U.K. drivers are not normally allowed to park on them at any time. To show clearly where these lines end, they must terminate with a short 'T' crossbar. These do and so they comply with Department for Transport Regulations. If you decide to park on this double-yellow and get a ticket, tough.\\n\\nNow, the slightly more interesting lines.\\n\\nThe two broken white lines at 90\\xba to the kerb show the end of parking bays. Look carefully and you'll see that, at one time, both bays had a double white end line - but one line has been painted out. (I took both photos at night. The camera flash makes the one on the left look more distinct than it really is. In fact both superfluous second lines are overpainted.)\\n\\nDepartment for Transport (DfT) regulations* stipulate that parking bays should have a single white broken end line, unless they have individual bays marked out for each vehicle. In which case they need double end lines.\\n\\nIn the photos above, Waltham Forest \\u2013 or maybe its contractors \\u2013 originally got it wrong. But while double white end lines were originally painted in error, the extra lines had been painted over. So the marking did comply with DfT Regulations. \\n\\nI've no idea how many parking bay lines were corrected by Waltham Forest. But they realised these were non-compliant; so got them marked correctly. By the way, this is not guesswork. I emailed Waltham Forest Parking Service and checked the position.\\n \\nThe First Secret \\n\\nI promised to tell you three secrets. Here's the first. Thousands of roads in (probably) hundreds of local authorities are not (or were not) properly marked according to the DfT regulations. These local councils knew and know this. Some - like Waltham Forest - did the decent and proper thing and corrected them. \\n\\nIn mid-2008 many London boroughs \\u2013 through London Councils their taxpayer-funded quango - were in discussion with Department for Transport civil servants to get a different solution. They wanted Rosie Winterton M.P. (then Minister of State for Transport) to give "temporary authorisation" letting them continue ignoring the DfT regulations with impunity for a further two years. \\n\\nThis amnesty on rule-breaking was not granted. Had it been, it would have applied only to local councils - not to drivers. \\n\\nAnd perversely, it would have rewarded those local councils who \\u2013 asleep at the management wheel \\u2013 failed to spot that their staff (or contractors) painted the wrong road markings. Or when they did notice, failed to insist the job was redone correctly. \\n\\nWas it reasonable to give local councils a bit more time to get their traffic lines repainted correctly? Of course. Though if I was the Minister I\\u2019d give weeks or at most a few months - not years. And I\\u2019d ask what steps \\u2013 if any \\u2013 each council had already taken to put its mistakes right.\\n\\nSecond Secret. \\n\\nIf you've read this far, you've realised the problem is not just one white line or two, or a few missing 'T'-bars. There are important principles at stake. \\n\\n \\u25ba Elected local councils are not above the law. And by the way, there is no very small print somewhere which says: "Except for parking lines and signs."\\n\\n\\u25ba Public confidence in public officials is undermined when they abuse their powerful position to play fast and loose with the rules.\\n\\nSo much for the principles.\\n\\nThe Third Secret \\n\\nNow let\\u2019s look at what's really bothering many Town Halls up and down the country. Money. \\n\\nTraffic fines are now a major part of many local councils' income. So when road lines or signs are wrong, drivers can appeal the \\u201cPenalty Charges\\u201d (traffic fines) and local councils lose income. If there are major blunders, thousands of people may appeal, clogging up the system. They could even start demanding their money back. \\n\\nIn some places, incompetent Parking and Highway Departments and/or their inept contractors have raised incorrect road lines and signs to an art form. As a result, many local councils may face potential holes in their budgets. Naturally, they wanted the Government to turn a blind eye and bail them out.\\n\\n____________________________________________________________\\n\\n\\xa7 Check this yourself *. See the: Traffic Signs Regulations and General Directions 2002. \\nDepartment for Transport's Traffic Signs Manual. ( Page 123; diagram 10.28 )\\n\\xa7 Click here to read more and see other examples.\\n\\xa7 Ticketfighter website gives examples of local councils elsewhere whose parking enforcement staff seem to think they are above the law."}

Hawaii became the 50th state months later on August 21, 1959.\\n\\nBeing late admittees into the Union the Natives of both Alaska and Hawaii have probably received more legal advantages in the US over those Natives in the contiguous 48 states.\\n\\nFor example, there is only one Indian Reservation in Alaska called Metlakatla in southeast Alaska. All other tribes have formed corporations where each corporation owns its own land. Many of the newer buildings being built in downtown Anchorage are property of one of the various tribal corporations."}

She is a Spayed Female, Shorthaired, Silver Grey Lop Bunny. She is large and approximately 3 years old. Trixie had been adopted but was returned because the owners got a new big dog and the dog and Trixie did not get along. The dog took over her space. Trixie is a beautiful bunny with a soft thick silvery grey coat. She also has a great personality and loves to be held and snuggled. Trixie likes to be carried around cradled like a baby. She is litterbox trained and keeps her space neat and clean. She would love a bunny safe exercise yard and likes to be outside. So if you have a bunny proof house and no canines on the premises maybe Trixie is the pet for you. You can see some additional images of Trixie as well as images of last week's Pet of the Week, Harley."}

creator: Len Blumin
title: Little Blue Heron
meta_data: {"pub_date": "1211040063", "date_taken": "2008-04-09 08:11:51", "description": "Went to Florida (Tarpon Springs) in April on a family visit, but of course took our scopes and gear for the chance outing. First morning there on a walk around the condo we saw this Little Blue Heron (Egretta cerulea) hunting is a grassy field. Patti soon discerned that it was catching grasshoppers. Opportunistic feeders, these herons. The Ciconiiformes rule in Florida, as virtually all U.S. members of this order can be found, mostly of them in good numbers and in many locations.  And, "Yes, the bill really is that blue." \\n\\nOrder: Ciconiiformes (Herons, Egrets, Bitterns, Ibises, Spoonbills, New World Vultures, Flamingos)\\n\\nFamily: Ardeidae (Herons, Egrets, Bitterns)\\n\\nGenus: Egretta (Includes of course both herons, like the Little Blue, and Egrets, like the Snowy Egret)\\n\\nSpecies: Egretta caerulea - Little Blue Heron. A lot like the Snowy Egret, but with thicker, black tipped and slightly downcurved bill. The Juvenile Little Blue has white plumage, so the bill helps tell it quickly from the Snowy egret. Have heard that the two species can interbreed."}

creator: Mexicaans fotomagazijn
meta_data: {"pub_date": "1211146361", "date_taken": "2008-05-15 19:19:00", "description": "Los Mochis, Sinaloa, M\\xe9xico. 15 de mayo de 2008, Concha Ac\\xfastica de la Escuela Vocacional de Artes. \\n\\nIn the early 90's, before the creation of Jumbo, Castillo, Charly, Eddie, Chuy Guerra, Javier Oth\\xf3n and Ren\\xe9 Garza formed a band called "Blueswagen" which played mainly covers of bands like The Beatles, The Rolling Stones, The Doors, Pink Floyd, R.E.M., U2, The Police, Lenny Kravitz, Stone Temple Pilots and Red Hot Chili Peppers. They started gaining more fans and an increasing popularity, which led to playing bars and clubs and recording many demos. BMG obtained one of the demos and started looking for them. Later the band signed with them.\\n\\nIn 1996, Flip joined the band and in 1997 Bugs, Eddie's brother, returned from Quintana Roo, Mexico and also joined the band. They changed the band's name to "Jumbo", after an Asian baby boy named Jumbo Jin Li who weighed at the time approximately 50 kg.\\n\\nIn 1997 and 1998, they recorded their first album, "Restaurant", which included the singles "Monotransistor", "Siento que...", "Aqu\\xed" and "Fotograf\\xeda", songs which were well received by the public.\\n\\nIn May 2005, brothers Eddie and Bugs Wako left the band. Bugs moved with his wife to Los Angeles, while Eduardo left the band so he could pursue different musical projects.\\n\\nJumbo es el nombre de un grupo de m\\xfasica rock originario de Monterrey, M\\xe9xico que forma parte del movimiento musical llamado Avanzada regia. Surge a ra\\xedz de una banda llamada Blueswagen (1994), donde Castillo (vocalista) y Charly (bajista) junto con Edy, Rana y Chuy Guerra comenzaron a tocar los fines de semana en la ciudad de Monterrey, dentro del circuito de bares de Rock & Roll. Blueswagen graba 12 tracks en un demo de estudio,bajo la producci\\xf3n de Jesus Flores con lo que atraen la atenci\\xf3n de varios sellos discogr\\xe1ficos. \\n\\nEl grupo estaba ya formado con la llegada del baterista Enrique Gonzalez Jr. (Hijo del famoso locutor de radio Enrique Gonzalez "El monstruo" y la cantante Vianey Valdez), integr\\xe1ndose a Clemente Castillo (voz y guitarra), Flip (guitarra), Charly (bajo) y Eddy (teclados, moog voz y coros), hermano de Enrique. El nombre lo tomaron de una publicaci\\xf3n amarillista, en portada aparec\\xeda un ni\\xf1o chino que naci\\xf3 pesando 6 kilos llamado Jumbo Yin Li. Al a\\xf1o siguiente Jumbo colabora en el disco Un Tributo a Jos\\xe9 Jos\\xe9, (homenaje a Jos\\xe9 Jos\\xe9, que despu\\xe9s gener\\xf3 una hola de tributos a distintos artistas latinos) con la canci\\xf3n Lo Dudo. Jumbo fue la \\xfanica banda que le dio otra melod\\xeda y transform\\xf3 totalmente la canci\\xf3n, llamando mucho la atenci\\xf3n. \\n\\nA mediados de 1999 sale al mercado Restaurant; Un disco muy melodioso y la mismo tiempo bastante explosivo con bastantes influencias de Blur, Radiohead y The Beatles. Su primer sencillo Monotransistor, mostraba un sonido explosivo y efusivo, y le seguir\\xeda un himno de la avanzada regia; Siento que, canci\\xf3n muy mel\\xf3dica de la mano con un gran video, considerado una de los mejores hechos en la historia del rock nacional y nominado a "Video de la Gente" por parte de MTV. Su tercer single ser\\xeda Aqu\\xed y posteriormente Fotograf\\xeda con el cual se oyeron en todo Am\\xe9rica Latina con un gran \\xe9xito comercial.\\n\\nD.D. y Ponle Play, el segundo disco de Jumbo, gener\\xf3 mucha expectativa y fu\\xe9 lanzado a a mediados de 2001. Este disco tiene una clara muestra mel\\xf3dica de principio a fin, siendo Rockstar el primer sencillo, que en palabras del comunicador regiomantano Juan Ramon Palacios era una alusi\\xf3n a la famosa frase regiomontana "No le pegues al Careca". Este disco coincide con los lanzamientos de Maquillaje de Zurdok y de Kinky, poniendo a la m\\xfasica de Monterrey en lo m\\xe1s alto. La similitud del sonido del Maquillaje y del D.D. y ponle play hacen que las bandas creadoras de estos discos se unan para realizar una gira por M\\xe9xico y Estados Unidos, acompa\\xf1ados por Kinky como talonero y de Zo\\xe9. A la par, Jumbo lanza Cada vez Que... con otro excelente video que de nueva cuenta los pone nominados en la categor\\xeda "Video de la Gente Latino Norte" de los Premios MTV 2001. Le sigui\\xf3 la canci\\xf3n D\\xeda, que sin tener video paso inadvertida. El tema Despu\\xe9s es un tema claramente rom\\xe1ntico que le vali\\xf3 a Jumbo unas semanas en el top 10 de MTV y Telehit. Justo cuando todo mundo cre\\xeda que el disco ya no daba otro sencillo, lanzanron el tema C\\xe1mara Lenta y un video majestuoso influenciado por el video Take On Me de A-ha. Destacan de este disco otras canciones como Audiorama, Motocicleta, Hoy as\\xed como el Intro y el Outro con la voz de Enrique Gonzalez padre.\\n\\nA mediados del 2003 lanzan Teleparque. Con este disco jumbo perdi\\xf3 mucho de su encanto musical, ya que el disco no sonaba ni mel\\xf3dico ni explosivo. Su primer single "En repetici\\xf3n", son\\xf3 bastante en la radio pero no funcion\\xf3 como ellos esperaban, el disco trataba de combinar la m\\xfasica actual con sus discos anteriores, adem\\xe1s de querer agregar sonidos de vanguardia. Un claro ejemplo fue su sencillo Bajo Control; tan s\\xf3lo dos singles y Jumbo parec\\xeda destinado a morir. Se destacan otras canciones como Black party, Estampida y Se derrumba.\\n\\nEl cuarto disco, Gran Panor\\xe1mico fue lanzado en el 2005. Este disco fue el fin de una era de Jumbo; Se despiden de la banda los hermanos Eddy y Enrique Gonzalez (Teclista y baterista respectivamente), dejando al grupo sin la "esencia Beatlesca" que estos le daban. En este disco se incluyen los videos de la banda en un DVD adicional, y contiene adem\\xe1s una recopilcaci\\xf3n de \\xe9xitos junto con dos nuevas canciones in\\xe9ditas: Hasta que el sol se apague y desprendi\\xe9ndose como sencillo la canci\\xf3n "Caminando hacia atras". Es en este disco donde se lanza el video del sencillo "D\\xeda", creado por Vinnie Veritas y dibujado totalmente a mouse.\\n\\nEl quinto disco, Superficie sali\\xf3 con un \\xe9xito gracias al rockampeonato y con sencillos como Un mill\\xf3n de vueltas."}

meta_data: {"pub_date": "1211189895", "date_taken": "2008-05-19 11:38:15", "description": "L'espart bord \\xe9s una planta herb\\xe0cia perennif\\xf2lia molt resistent de la fam\\xedlia de les gram\\xednies que viu en terrenys semi\\xe0rids i erms de sec\\xe0.\\nArriba a fer al voltant d'1 m d'altura.\\nLes seves fulles s\\xf3n primes i llargues, de color verd grog\\xf3s. \\nFloreix a la primavera. Les flors formen una espigueta amb molts p\\xe8ls sedosos, embolcallats per una br\\xe0ctea gran en forma de beina.\\nA les zones mediterr\\xe0nies l'espart bord s'ha utilitzat des de molt antic per a la fabricaci\\xf3 d'objectes d'espart. Al Segri\\xe0 es feien una mena de cordes trenades anomenades vencills. Tamb\\xe9 s'ha emprat per per fer pasta de paper.\\nEl albard\\xedn es una planta herb\\xe1cea perennifolia muy resistente de la familia de las gram\\xedneas que vive en terrenos semi\\xe1ridos y yermos de secano.\\nLlega a medir hasta 1 m de altura.\\nSus hojas son delgadas y largas, de color verde amarillento.\\nFlorece en primavera. Las flores forman una espiguilla con muchos pelos sedosos, envueltos por una br\\xe1ctea grande en forma de vaina.\\nEn las zonas mediterr\\xe1neas el albard\\xedn se ha utilizado desde muy antiguo para la fabricaci\\xf3n de objetos de esparto. En el Segri\\xe0 (Lleida) se hac\\xedan una especie de cuerdas trenzadas lamadas "vencills". Tambi\\xe9n se ha utilizado para hacer pasta de papel."}

meta_data: {"pub_date": "1211223395", "date_taken": "2008-05-19 11:56:35", "description": "Tanto La Tercera como El Mercurio, dos de los principales medios nacionales, incluyeron entrevistas que me hicieron para sus ediciones especiales en conmemoraci\\xf3n del El D\\xeda Mundial de las Telecomunicaciones y de la Sociedad de la Informaci\\xf3n (DMTSI) publicadas el pasado Viernes 16 de Mayo en formato impreso y digital.\\n\\nEn la entrevista para El Mercurio, enfatic\\xe9 la importancia de enfrentar el problema de la brecha digital: \\n\\n\\u201cA nivel de los organismos p\\xfablicos el enfrentar este problema supone cambiar el enfoque de los temas TICs quitando protagonismo a las tecnolog\\xedas (hardware y software) y focaliz\\xe1ndose m\\xe1s en los procesos sociales que se potencian gracias a ellas.Esto es a\\xfan m\\xe1s importante en sociedades con tantos problemas de desigualdad como Chile. Por ende, el Estado y sus organismos deben avanzar hacia un enfoque basado en \\u201cPol\\xedticas Tecnolog\\xedas para la Equidad\\u201d, las que se deben incorporar como un componente permanente de la acci\\xf3n p\\xfablica en todos sus \\xe1mbitos\\u201d\\n\\nEn el caso de La Tercera, fui consultado por los aspectos m\\xe1s destacados y las falencias que presenta la Estrategia Digital de Chile. \\n\\nAmbos art\\xedculos est\\xe1n disponibles on-line"}

creator: peterjr1961
title: Roman Marble Sarcophagus with the Four Season Referenced in Relief (detail lid reliefs: Eros in chariot pulled by bulls[fall])
meta_data: {"pub_date": "1211258084", "date_taken": "2008-02-28 10:34:44", "description": "Marble sarcophagus with garlands and the myth of Theseus and Ariadne\\nRoman, Hadrianic or early Antonine, ca. A.D. 130\\u2013150\\n\\nFound at Capranica, near Rome, in 1889\\n\\nOn the lid, shown in delicate low relief, winged erotes drive chariots drawn by animals associated with the four seasons: bears with spring, lions with summer, bulls with fall, and boars with winter. On the front, four erotes bear seasonal garlands composed of flowers, wheat, grapes, pomegranates, and laurel. Between the swags are three episodes from the myth of the Greek hero Theseus. With the help of the Cretan princess Ariadne, Theseus slew the Minotaur, a part-bull and part-human monster who was caged in a labyrinth, where he consumed Athenian boys and girls sent as annual tribute. Depicted from left to right are: Ariadne giving a thread to Theseus at the entrance to the labyrinth, Theseus slaying the Minotaur, and the sleeping Ariadne abandoned on the island of Naxos, where she will be awakened by the god Dionysos to become his immortal bride."}

creator: Skelekitty (Krissi Sandvik)
title: green glass and green grass - Baker, NV
meta_data: {"pub_date": "1211319712", "date_taken": "2008-05-03 22:57:06", "description": "You'll see a number of tongue-in-cheek "fence-art" sculptures along the roads leading to and from Baker. Termed "Post-Impression Art" by local residents (because the art is mounted on fence posts). The movement began in the mid-1990's when "Doc" Sherman created the "Permanent Wave Society." This sculpture consisted of rubber gloves filled with cement (get it? permanent wave?) and mounted on the tops of fence posts. Since then Doc and others have added spontaneous contributions of whimsical art on fence posts along roads around Baker.  Doc's artistic endeavors have been amazing therapy for him as he was partially paralyzed by a crippling stroke. He continues to create new pieces on occasion and his sense of humor and creativity have brought many smiles and laughter to residents and travelers alike."}

creator: Marcio Cabral de Moura
title: Pante\xe3o da Fran\xe7a / France Pantheon
meta_data: {"pub_date": "1211421214", "date_taken": "2007-01-11 15:59:18", "description": "O Pante\\xe3o (ou Panth\\xe9on) de Paris \\xe9 um edif\\xedcio situado no monte de Santa Genoveva, no 5.\\xba arrondissement de Paris, em pleno Quartier Latin. \\xc0 sua volta disp\\xf5em-se alguns edif\\xedcios de import\\xe2ncia, como a igreja de Saint-\\xc9tienne-du-Mont, a Biblioteca de Santa Genoveva, a Universidade de Paris-I (Panth\\xe9on-Sorbonne), a prefeitura do 5.\\xba arrondissement e o Liceu Henrique IV. Da rua Soufflot consegue-se uma perspectiva favor\\xe1vel do Pante\\xe3o, a partir do Jardim do Luxemburgo.\\n\\nTem 110 metros de largura e 84 metros de largura. A fachada principal est\\xe1 decorada com um p\\xf3rtico de colunas de estilo cor\\xedntio que apoiam um front\\xe3o triangular da autoria David d'Angers. O edif\\xedcio, em forma de cruz grega, \\xe9 coroado por uma c\\xfapula de 83 metros de altura, com um lanternim no topo. O seu interior est\\xe1 decorado por pinturas acad\\xe9micas de Puvis de Chavannes, Gros e Cabanel, entre outros.\\nWikip\\xe9dia\\nParis, Fran\\xe7a\\n\\nParis, France\\nThe Panth\\xe9on (Latin Pantheon, from Greek Pantheon, meaning "All the Gods") is a building in the Latin Quarter in Paris, France. It was originally built as a church dedicated to St. Genevieve, but after many changes now combines liturgical functions with its role as a famous burial place. It is an early example of Neoclassicism, with a fa\\xe7ade modelled on the Pantheon in Rome, surmounted by a small dome that owes some of its character to Bramante's "Tempietto". Located in the 5th arrondissement on the Montagne Sainte-Genevi\\xe8ve, the Panth\\xe9on looks out over all of Paris. Its architect, Jacques-Germain Soufflot, had the intention of combining the lightness and brightness of the gothic cathedral with classical principles. Soufflot died before his work was achieved, and his plans were not entirely followed. The transparency he had planned for his masterpiece was not attained. Nevertheless, it is one of the most important architectural achievements of its time and the first great neoclassical monument.\\nWikipedia"}

creator: infomatique
title: Africa Day 2008 - Dublin Castle
meta_data: {"pub_date": "1211744455", "date_taken": "2008-05-25 12:49:54", "description": "Ireland's black community was embraced at the Africa Day festival in the grounds of Dublin Castle. Sinead O'Connor, Kila, Mundy, and Republic of Loose performed at the free family event alongside Ugandan drummers, Kenyan acrobats, traditional Nigerian dancers, Congolese folk singers and gospel choirs. More than 40,000 people born in Africa are living in Ireland, with the majority coming from Nigeria, South Africa, Zimbabwe and the Congo. Census figures showed that 20,000 of those were living in the capital.\\n\\nThe Minister made a short speech explaining how welcome Africans are in Ireland and that Africa Day was first celebrated here three years ago. He said that the party is getting much bigger and that it is hoped that it will be even bigger next year with better entertainment an bands (I assume that he was not saving that the entertainment available today needed to be better because it was excellent)."}

creator: infomatique
title: Africa Day 2008 - Dublin Castle
meta_data: {"pub_date": "1211746431", "date_taken": "2008-05-25 13:14:42", "description": "More than 7000 people converged on Dublin Castle today to celebrate Africa Day.\\n\\nThe event was the only one of its kind celebrating the African Union to take place outside of the African continent.\\n\\nTraditional song, dance and crafts from all parts of the continent were on display at the event.\\n\\n'Ireland has a long history of association with the continent of Africa through the Irish missionaries and NGOs but more recently through immigration,' Minister for Integration, Conor Lenihan said at the event.\\n\\n'According to the Census of 2006 Africans now make up 8% of Ireland's new communities,' he said.\\n\\n'In the light of these strong connections it is only appropriate that we celebrate this day,' he added\\n\\nMusical guests such as Mundy, Sinead O'Connor, The Republic of Loose, Kila and a number of African entertainers performed at the event."}

meta_data: {"pub_date": "1211817343", "date_taken": "2008-05-09 08:33:46", "description": "View large\\nA milky stork posing at the largest covered bird park in the world in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.\\n\\nThey are found in lowlands, salt water marshes, and mangrove swamps of Cambodia, Vietnam, Malaysia, and Indonesia. Due to human disturbance of nesting colonies, habitat loss and destruction of mangroves, poaching, and rice- and fish-farming, the milky stork is an endangered species with less than 5,000 remaining in the world today!\\n\\nMilky storks build their nests in tall trees during the months of October through December. Nests are built of dried twigs and branches, arranged in big piles between tree branches. As many as 8 pairs may build their nests in one tree."}
